opout rates. Such evidence-based techniques will help therapists establish proper roles and behaviors, work with client preferences, educate clients on patterns of change, and plan for appropriate termination within the first few sessions. Additional strategies can be used throughout therapy to help strengthen and reinforce clients' feelings of hope, enhance their motivation to create change, develop and maintain the therapeutic alliance, and continually evaluate overall treatment progress. Case examples demonstrate how these strategies can be employed in real-life scenarios"--Publicity materials. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2014 APA, all rights reserved).  aElectronic reproduction.bWashington, D.C. :cAmerican Psychological Association,d2014.nAvailable via World Wide Web.nAccess limited by licensing agreement.7s2014 dcunns  a21 44 5712aPatient Dropoutsxpsychology.12aPsychotherapyvmethods.12aTreatment Refusalxpsychology.22aProfessional-Patient Relations. 0aPatient refusal of treatment. 0aPsychotherapyxMethodology. 0aPatientsxPsychology.1 aGreenberg, Roger P.403University of Alberta Accessuhttp://ovidsp.ovid.com/ovidweb.cgi?T=JS&NEWS=N&PAGE=toc&SEARCH=2014-16767.dd&LINKTYPE=asBody&D=psbk403MacEwan University Accessuhttp://search.ebscohost.com/direct.asp?db=pzh&jid=%22201416767%22&scope=site403Concordia University of Edmonton Accessuhttp://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=pzh&jid=201416767&site=ehost-live  hUAINzPSYCBOOKS  hUAINmCONCORDIAzPSYCBKSCON  hUAINmGR_MAC_INTzPSYCBKSGM  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6700465-1001lINTERNETmUAINTERNETrYsYtE-RESOURCEu9/30/2014xE-BOOKzPSYCBOOKS  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6700465-2001lINTERNETmCONCORDIArYsYtE-RESOURCEu9/30/2014xE-BOOKzPSYCBKSCON  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6700465-3001lINTERNETmGR_MAC_INTrYsYtE-RESOURCEu9/30/2014xE-BOOKzPSYCBKSGM01ahttp://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n85119001bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/312962196